 $x,y\gt 0.$ let $a:=\frac xt,\ a^2:=\frac {x^2}{t^2},\ b:=\frac yt,\ b^2:=\frac {y^2}{t^2}.$ Find out some interesting properties. </think> <answer>Then, the given $x,y,k$ condition becomes
\begin{align*} \quad & a^2+b^2\ge 2ab \quad \text{(by AM-GM)} \\ \quad & a^4+b^4\ge 2a^2b^2 \quad \text{(by AM-GM)} \\ \quad & \sqrt{ab}\le\frac{a+b}2 \quad \text{(by AM-GM)}\end{align*}
As I already planned $u:=ab\ge 0$, these $3$ inequalities become\begin{align*} \quad & u^2+(u-\sqrt{u})^2\ge u^2-2u\sqrt{u}+u^2 \quad (u\ge 0) \\ \quad & 4u^2 \ge (u^2+4u+4)^2 \quad (u\ge 0). \end{align*}We get\begin{align*} 5u^4-18u^3+13u^2-4u\le 0,\quad u^2-4u+4 \le 0\quad (u\ge 0) \\ \Leftrightarrow u(u-2)^2(5u-12) \le 0 , \quad (u-2)^2 \le 0 , \quad (u\ge 0) \\ \Leftrightarrow u\le 5/2 , \quad u=2,\quad u\ge 0\\ \Leftrightarrow \frac{x^2}{y^2}+\frac{y^2}{x^2} \le \frac52,\quad xy=2,\quad t>0.\end{align*}
So, the best possible value of $k=t$ is $\sqrt{\frac52}$</answer>

